{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at a module boundary (file discovery/parsing -> execution sequencing), not a single pure function. A realistic test should wire discovery plus runner plus migration-executor/repo and assert actual execution order. Higher levels were considered and rejected: no behavior text requires real OS/network/subprocess faults (so not System), no AI output dependency (not Agentic/Workflow).","test_description":"Create a temp migrations directory with out-of-order filenames (e.g., 001, 010, 002), run the runner against a test DB/repo, and assert migrations executed in numeric-prefix order and recorded in that same order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The bug appears when runner logic interacts with persisted migration state across runs (runner <-> _migrations table/repo), so Unit is too low. Integration is sufficient because this is deterministic state handoff; no required real OS/network/subprocess behavior is stated, and no model judgment is involved. Higher levels rejected by behavior text: this is about 'already been applied' metadata lookup, not infrastructure failure handling.","test_description":"Run migrations once, then run the runner again against the same test database. Assert no previously applied migration SQL is executed on the second run and no duplicate metadata rows are inserted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails